TY  - GEN
TI  - Analyzing Redox-Active Polymer Films in Organic Radical Batteries Through Electron Paramagnetic Resonance-Enabled Modifiable Electrochemical Cell Design
AU  - Zhang Min Min
PY  - 2026
DO  - 10.2139/ssrn.6626949
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.6626949
AB  - This paper describes the design and construction of a flexible, inexpensive electrochemical cell for in situ X-band (9–10 GHz) EPR scanning. The main purpose of this study is to look at the electrochemical properties of redox-active polymer films in polar organic electrolytes at ambient temperature. One way to observe charge-transfer processes in conductive polymer materials is to directly apply a layer of the material over a platinum wire working electrode. across a range of experimental conditions and improves electrochemical performance while reducing ohmic losses. Here, we demonstrate how well poly[N, N-bis(3-(4-oxy(2,2,6,6-tetramethylpiperidin-1-oxyl) butoxy)salicylidene) ethylenediimide nickel(II)] works. This means it might be a good cathode material for organic radical batteries. Continuous-wave EPR investigations may reveal the charge state of a material and how it behaves when it is oxidized and reduced, among other electrochemical properties. The cell can be 3D-printed and is inexpensive, making it a potential instrument for advanced electrochemical characterisation. This might help research organizations that don&apos;t have much money obtain access to these technologies. This is significant for policy reasons. Because it can work with diverse electrode materials and testing methods, it may be used more in schools, renewable energy technologies, and battery research.
