TY  - JOUR
TI  - Manufacturing of ultra-thin redox-active polymer films using the layer-by-layer method and co-polymerization of vinyl viologen units
AU  - Carmen-Simona Jordan (Asaftei)
PY  - 2022
DO  - 10.5802/crchim.182
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5802/crchim.182
AB  - The current study presents the principle of a new approach to fabricating redox-active polymers film on mesoporous TiO 2 electrodes. This new strategy involves the top-down approach (adsorption) combined with bottom-up layer-by-layer (LbL) crosslinking and “ in situ ” co-polymerization reactions. This approach uses 4,4 ′ -bipyridinium units, so-called viologen with an anchoring phosphono ethyl acid and the vinyl group as building blocks molecules, and 1,3,5-tris-(bromomethyl) benzene as crosslinker. Crosslinking and co-polymerization reactions lead to the growth of the concentration of redox species on the surface and increased stability of the colored areas towards forced desorption in water. The method offers a simple, versatile way to manufacture nanostructured functional materials.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
TI  - Theta Point Calculation of a Polymer Chain with Electric Dipole Moments: Monte Carlo Simulation
AU  - Şahin UYAVER
PY  - 2020
DO  - 10.16984/saufenbilder.710797
UR  - https://doi.org/10.16984/saufenbilder.710797
AB  - Monte Carlo simulations are used to simulate a single polymer chain in a more generalized model. The more generalized model differs from the simpler models by including dipole-dipole interactions. The polymer chain is modeled as a freely rotating chain where the neighboring beads are connected by harmonic spring. Excluded volume effects are included employing modified Lennard-Jones potential. As the extension in this work, each monomer unit carries permanently a freely-rotating electric dipole moment. After getting the system equilibrated the average values are measured and Θ-temperature of the system is determined. The effects of the presence of the dipole moments to the Θ-temperature of the system are investigated. The results are analyzed in comparison with a bare model.
ER  - 

TY  - GEN
TI  - Multi-Scale Mechanical Properties of Bulk-Heterojunction Films in Polymer Solar Cells
AU  - Biao Xiao
AU  - Tian Zhong
AU  - Feng Guo
AU  - Shiyun Lei
AU  - Qingduan Li
AU  - Tao Jia
AU  - Xunchang Wang
AU  - Renqiang Yang
PY  - 2022
DO  - 10.21203/rs.3.rs-2133911/v1
UR  - https://doi.org/10.21203/rs.3.rs-2133911/v1
AB  - Abstract The mechanical properties of ¬bulk-heterojunction (BHJ) films play critical roles in the operational stability of flexible polymer solar cells (PSCs). However, research on the mechanical properties of BHJ films is far behind the studies on their optoelectronic properties. Herein, investigations are conducted to systematically evaluate the multi-scale mechanical properties of the BHJ films. The fullerene derivative PC71BM, the fused ring non-fullerene electron acceptor Y6, and the polymer acceptor PRi-C39 are selected as the acceptor materials of the BHJ films for comparative analysis. Interestingly, the tensile moduli of the films based on PC71BM, Y6, and PRi-C39 measured by using the “film-on-water” (FOW) method decrease sequentially, and their fracture strain and toughness show an increasing trend. Moreover, the nanoindentation moduli of the BHJ films based on different electron acceptors vary in accordance with the results of FOW characterizations, and their moduli and hardness distributions are uniform in these films. Time-dependent creep analyses from both macroscopic tensile measurements and microscopic indentation characterizations illustrate that the occurrence of creep deformation in the PC71BM, Y6 and PRi-C39 based films decrease sequentially. Contact angle tests demonstrate that the main reason for the different mechanical properties in these films is the varied interactions between the donor and the acceptors. All results above demonstrate the effects of acceptor type on the multi-scale mechanical properties of the BHJ films, which are of great importance for the designing of novel electron acceptor materials and manufacturing of reliable flexible PSCs.
ER  - 

